The other side of N cycling is that nearly half of the fertilizer N applied in agriculture is leaked into the environment resulting in various negative environmental externalities (Canfield et al., 2010; Galloway et al., 2008; Phoenix et al., 2006; Schlesinger, 2009; Vitousek et al., 2009), with the possibility that we have transgressed the sustainable planetary “boundary” for N (Steffen et al., 2015). When applied in excess, reactive forms of N (ammonia, nitrate, nitrogen oxides) are lost to the environment through volatilization, leaching or emissions (Battye et al., 2017; Sutton et al., 2013) causing multiple adverse effects on terrestrial and aquatic systems and on human health (Table 1
                     ). Fertilizer N is held responsible for a nearly 20% increase in atmospheric nitrous oxide (N2O) since the industrial revolution (Park et al., 2012). Notably, more anthropogenic N has been released to the environment than CO2 during recent decades (Fig. 1
                     ), leading Battye et al. (2017) to ask whether “nitrogen is the next carbon?”

Synthetic N has been the major source of N applied to meet 50–57% of total N requirement of cropland and pasture lands globally (Table 2). Of the 43–50% of N coming from other sources, BNF contributed approximately 43–44%, whereas deposition 36%, manure 34%, and crop residue 30% are the rest. Among the outputs, crop harvest ranged from 36% to 42% and losses from 57% to 64%. Recently, Ladha et al. (2016a) constructed a top-down global N budget for maize, rice, and wheat. Of the 100 Tg of synthetic N, approximately 50% is currently used in the cultivation of three major cereals (maize, 16%; rice, 16%; and wheat, 18%) globally. The N budget sheet for maize, rice, and wheat was developed for a 50-year period (1961–2010) by integrating global quantities of various sources and sinks of N, which were easier to estimate, rather than assessing N losses, which are highly location and management specific. A total of 1551 Tg of N were harvested by these cereals during the period, of which 48% was derived from fertilizer N source. Around 4% was contributed through net soil depletion (Fig. 4
                     ). The major source of this N is apparently derived from the ecosystem service of non-symbiotic biological N2 fixation by free-living bacteria and cyanobacteria, contributing 25% of total N in the crop, which is equal to 13, 22, and 13kgNha−1
                     year−1 for maize, rice, and wheat, respectively (Ladha et al., 2016a). Other non-fertilizer and non-soil sources include manure (14%) and atmospheric deposition (6%), while crop residues and seed contribute marginally (2% and 1%, respectively) to crop N supply. These finding highlight the need to consider all sources of N [synthetic, manure/residue, deposition, symbiotic and non-symbiotic BNF and indigenous soil organic nitrogen (SON)] when designing strategies to improve the NUE.

With the conflicting dual role of N on agricultural systems and the environment—both positive and negative—the N challenge is highly relevant across most SDGs as described in Section 2 (Fig. 2). The human use of NR has profound beneficial and detrimental impacts. Its beneficial impacts result in food production and industrial applications. Detrimental impacts occur because most of the NR used in food production and the entire amount of NR formed during fossil fuel combustion are lost to the environment where it causes a cascade of environmental changes that can adversely affect both the people and the planet. Nitrogen influences the SDGs via a complex array of interactions that operate through climate systems, food production, human and ecosystem health, the provision of ecosystem services. Whereas in some cases these interactions involve trade-offs—the most obvious being the need to increase N (in regions with currently too little or sub-optimal use of N) to meet SDGs 1, 2, 3, 8, and 15 while reducing N in regions with current excess use to support SDG 13 and others (SDGs 3, 6, 7, 11, 14 and 15) (Fig. 8
                     , Table 4
                     ). Additionally, meeting some of SDGs can also enable optimum N application (Kanter et al., 2006). For example, quality education, women's empowerment, reduction in social inequalities, resolution of conflicts, and global partnerships can encourage farmers to move from too little or imbalanced fertilizer to a more agronomically optimum and economically sound rate. We provide an elaborated discussion about these SDGs in Section 7.3.

Although N fertilizer use in the USA has increased more slowly in the past two decades (Fig. 15
                           ), yields of all major crops have continued to increase. Because crop yields are closely related to N uptake (Cassman et al., 2002), these trends imply a steady increase in NUE and reduced N losses to the environment. Cassman et al. (2002) suggested that greater NUE has resulted from two factors: (1) steady improvement in the stress tolerance of maize hybrids that increases crop growth rates and allows sowing at higher plant densities, which together accelerate the establishment of a vigorous root system to intercept and acquire available N in the soil profile, and (2) development and adoption of technologies that may improve the synchrony between crop N demand and N supply. In addition to efforts to sustain soil quality, technologies comprising good agronomy include (a) fertilizer N application based on integrated management programs that incorporate soil test-based evidence, (b) split N fertilizer applications, (c) fertigation (the application of nitrogen and other nutrients through irrigation), (d) site-specific N management, and (e) new fertilizer formulations such as controlled release and nitrification inhibitors. Available data suggest that maize receiving the largest share of total N fertilizer in the U.S. (44% in 2005), had remarkably low NUE in the 1960s but resulted in impressive improvements of 50% NUE from the mid-1970s to early 2000s (Fig. 16
                           ). For example, average NUE in the U.S. required 1.0kg of applied N to produce 43kg of grain yield during 1974–76, whereas that same amount of N produced 65kg of grain during 2003–05 (USEPA, 2011). Such improvement in NUE resulted not only from improved crop varieties and good fertilizer management but also due to good policies and larger investment in research and education. Although considerable progress has been made in reducing N surplus and associated environmental problems, significant efforts are still needed to address the secondary N pollution problems (Bricker et al., 2008; USEPA, 2009, 2016).

Nutrients are used most efficiently when their availability is synchronized with crop demand. There are many management approaches available for increasing NUE through matching N supply with crop demand and thereby mitigating loss of N from agroecosystems. Some of the approaches have relatively higher relevance and impact in some regions and to some of SDGs (Table 6
                        ). Managing the right source at the right rate, right time and in the right place is best accomplished with the right tools and best management practices (see Section 8.3.2). A range of precision N tools (e.g., Green Seeker™ and the Nutrient Expert® decision support software) and techniques (e.g., direct drilling of fertilizer and fertigation) are now available to support best fertilizer management (Sapkota et al., 2014). These tools and techniques provide a means of fine-tuning N management decisions. For example, chlorophyll meter, the leaf color chart or optical sensors (e.g., the GreenSeeker that provides normalized differential vegetation index measurements) can be used to guide in-season N management (Sapkota et al., 2014). Similarly, computer/android phone-based decision support software (e.g., Nutrient Expert, Crop Manager) are being used to refine N management practices in farmers' fields in India, Mexico, and the United States. Such tools have become increasingly important in geographies where blanket fertilizer recommendations are the norm. Research by CIMMYT demonstrates that in a rice-wheat system, fertilizer efficiency can be increased by 10–15% due to better placement of fertilizer mechanized seed and fertilizer drilling compared with broadcasting in the conventional system (M.L. Jat, Personal Communication). In the Indo-Gangetic plains of India, both the Nutrient Expert® and GreenSeeker™-based nutrient management have increased the partial factor productivity of nitrogen in wheat compared with state-recommended and farmers' fertilizer practice (Sapkota et al., 2014) (Fig. 17
                        ). Through on-farm comparison in over 4000 farmers' field across Indo-Gangetic plains of India, CIMMYT found that the “nutrient expert”-based nutrient management reduced the GHG intensity of rice, wheat and maize production by 5–35% (average 13%). Similarly, Bijay-Singh (2016) showed significant improvement in rice yield, agronomic efficiency and recovery efficiency of N through GreenSeeker™ optical sensor based N application in rice in Punjab, India.

Genetic improvement of NUE through plant selection, breeding and genetic engineering has also been considered (Bogard et al., 2010; Ciampitti and Vyn, 2012; Haegele et al., 2013; Han et al., 2015; Hirel et al., 2007; Ladha et al., 1998; Lafitte and Edmeades, 1995; Lammerts van Bueren and Struik, 2017; Martin et al., 2006; McAllister et al., 2012; Sylvester-Bradley and Kindred, 2009). However, to our knowledge, there has been no breeding effort per se which aimed directly at improving fertilizer recovery efficiency. Instead studies focussed characterizing NUE related traits in diverse crop germplasm differing in grain yield potential. Broadly, two plant traits related to NUE are involved: N acquisition from soil and fertilizer N, and internal efficiency with which N is used to produce plant biomass and grains (Fig. 18
                        ). Differences in the efficiency of N acquisition may arise from differences in the (a) efficiency of absorption and assimilation of NH4
                        + and other N species; (b) root-induced changes in the rhizosphere affecting N mineralization, transformation and transport; and (c) root- and rhizosphere-associated BNF. Variations in the efficiency of internal use may arise from variances in (a) internal N requirements for growth, biomass production, and organ formation, (b) ability to translocate, distribute and remobilize absorbed N in various organs, (c) flag leaf N import/export and leaf senescence patterns, and (d) the efficiency of N use in converting CO2 to carbohydrates. The N acquisition trait of NUE appears to be important when N supply is limiting, which may exist in an unfavorable environment (Anzoua et al., 2010; Lafitte and Edmeades, 1995; Moll et al., 1982; Ortiz-Monasterio et al., 1997; Rao et al., 2018). However, both N acquisition and internal N efficiency traits in a favorable environment with non-limiting N supply appear to have already been taken care of in the high yielding varieties with high harvest indices (Peng and Cassman, 1998). Crop varieties with similar harvest indices may have slightly improved NUE through lower N concentrations in grain and straw, which however may not be acceptable to the consumers because this would reduce the protein contents in the produce (Ladha et al., 1998; Singh et al., 1998; Sylvester-Bradley and Kindred, 2009). In maize, more recent varieties have substantial improvement in internal N efficiency resulting in a lower grain N concentration (Ciampitti and Vyn, 2012; Scott et al., 2006; Singh et al., 1998), which again suggests that the improvement in NUE may have resulted from overall breeding for high grain yields. The selection and breeding efforts to improve crop NUE is also challenged from the fact that there are huge genotype environment and management (G×E×M) interactions. From a comprehensive review, Ciampitti and Vyn (2012) concluded that the future improvements in grain yield can increase the N recovery efficiency as concomitant effect of the strong linkages between grain, harvest index and N harvest index, and consequently promote further gains in total plant N uptake. The authors further suggest that higher NUE will need combined efforts into (a) determination of appropriate N rates for the specific G×E×M interaction environments, (b) improving plant N uptake (related to processes at soil- and plant-levels), and (c) augmenting the sink demand with sustainable source (i.e., functional photosynthesis-stay green). However, it is noteworthy that in case of rice, Peng and Cassman (1998) showed that N uptake capacity is not a constraint in modern cultivars with high yield potential provided an optimal N supply exists at times of high crop N demand.
